<TEXT>
   
   The Uptown String Quartet (<ORGANIZATION>Philips</ORGANIZATION>) _ <PERSON>Diane Monroe</PERSON> and <PERSON>Lesa
Terry</PERSON>, violins; <PERSON>Maxine Roach</PERSON>, viola; <PERSON>Eileen M. Folson</PERSON>, Cello.
   
   And now for something completely different ...
   A listener needs a change now and again, and this disc from the
Uptown String Quartet is spring cleaning for jaded ears.
   The name gives a clue _ a marriage of the string quartet with
the sounds from far uptown, beyond 110th Street in <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>. A big
shot of jazz, a little rag, a little blues, a lot of Polish.
   Listen to ``Midnight Child'' and it's evident why the mix is so
convincing. The virtuoso note-bending of the blues and gospel
singers was born for the violin. So, too, were the strutting
rhythms of ``Calvary,'' and doggone if <PERSON>Scott Joplin</PERSON> didn't have
strings in mind when he wrote ``Easy Winners.''
   It helps, too, that the four players are demon fiddlers, whose
various experiences include the <LOCATION>Philadelphia Orchestra</LOCATION>,
``Dreamgirls,'' the <LOCATION>New York Philharmonic</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Frank Sinatra</PERSON>, <PERSON>Sammy
Davis Jr.</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Wynton Marsalis</LOCATION> and producer <PERSON>Max Roach</PERSON>'s Double Quartet.
   Yes, it may seem a little strange, but this is no <ORGANIZATION>Beethoven</ORGANIZATION>'s
Ninth for massed accordion band kind of stunt. Each of a dozen cuts
is perfectly idiomatic, fresh, piquant, just right.
   The Uptown String Quartet threatens to give crossover recordings
a good name.
   _ By <PERSON>Robert Barr</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Associated Press Writer</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
