<CAPTION>  Photo; Photo: Judas Priest will be among the five heavy-metal acts at
Shoreline Sunday.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; SHOW; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THERE'S an invasion coming. It's big, it's bad, it's noisy, it packs some
awesome firepower, and if you get in its way it will roll over you like an M-1
tank.;    No. It isn't Desert Storm, The Sequel.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ROCK SLIDE
HEAP-O'-METAL TOUR WILL HAVE SONY ROLLING
IN HEAPS OF CASH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  MUSIC
(box) Alice Cooper: still shocking, Page 22  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     It's <ORGANIZATION>Operation Rock &amp; Roll</ORGANIZATION>. And in its way, it's just as scary.;    Think
of it. Five head-banging acts -- <PERSON>Judas Priest</PERSON>, <PERSON>Alice Cooper</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Motorhead</ORGANIZATION>,
Dangerous Toys and <ORGANIZATION>Metal Church</ORGANIZATION> -- all on the same stage going leather-bent
for hell in a heavy-metal basket, all at <ORGANIZATION>Shoreline Amphitheater</ORGANIZATION>, all on
Sunday.;    Awwwwwwright! Rocknnnnnnnrollllll! Getdowwwwwwn! Boooooogie!;   
There.;    Now that we've gotten that off our chest, we can get on with the
business at hand. Which is, oddly enough, the business of rock 'n' roll, which
is the basis of <ORGANIZATION>Operation Rock &amp; Roll.</ORGANIZATION>;    You thought this was an inspired
match made in metal heaven? Think again.;    <ORGANIZATION>Operation Rock &amp; Roll</ORGANIZATION> might be a
fan's delight -- six hours of metal madness. But it is also a part of the new
trend to market tours  like a <ORGANIZATION>Kellogg's Variety Pack</ORGANIZATION>. No more of those one-act
"An Evening With . . ." numbers. It's safety -- and ticket sales -- in
numbers, with groups being loaded onto tours to draw as many fans as
possible.;    In the case of the other tours such as the recent Gathering of
the Tribes and the upcoming <LOCATION>Lollapalooza</LOCATION> and Gang of Four/Public Enemy/Sisters
of Mercy/Warrior Soul slugfest, there has been an attempt to contribute to a
new openness in the music scene with an eclectic assortment of acts.;    But
not with <ORGANIZATION>Operation Rock &amp; Roll</ORGANIZATION>. It is strictly business. Pocket-calculator
time.;    All of the acts on this tour are allied in their affiliation with
the <ORGANIZATION>Columbia</ORGANIZATION> and Epic records labels (which are part of <ORGANIZATION>Sony Music</ORGANIZATION>). They
don't hang out at the local bar, swigging brewskies and clanging chords. Their
people got together with the <ORGANIZATION>Sony</ORGANIZATION> people and all of them decided that it was
time to cash in. (Ticket sales to the event are sluggish, tour sources say.); 
  And how will they cash in? Let us count the ways.;    For starters, there's
the "promotion-only" Operation Rock &amp; Roll audio cassette which comes with
songs by the five participating groups. A quarter-million of these have been
printed up for the tour to be used as giveaways in conjunction with local
shows. The first few thousand fans who get to each venue will also get free
copies. Nice, eh? Yes, but the cassette also comes with songs by other
<ORGANIZATION>Columbia</ORGANIZATION> and Epic acts, including <LOCATION>Fishbone</LOCATION>, War Babies and Cycle Sluts From
Hell, all the better to promote their records.;    Then there is the <ORGANIZATION>Operation
Rock &amp; Roll</ORGANIZATION> edition of <ORGANIZATION>MJI Broadcasting</ORGANIZATION>'s syndicated "Metalshop" program,
which was aired <DATE>July 4</DATE>. It came with interviews with the tour's groups and
selections of their music.;    Then there is the new "Operation Rock &amp; Roll"
video (<ORGANIZATION>Sony Music</ORGANIZATION>) that was released <DATE>July 2</DATE>, just in time for start of the
tour <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Salt Lake City</LOCATION>. It comes with videos by the groups of the
tour, for <MONEY>$19.95</MONEY>.;    Have we forgotten anything?;  Yes, there is music
involved in all of this. And -- given its metal base -- some of it might be
quite good. With its legal problems of <DATE>1990</DATE> resolved -- remember the <ORGANIZATION>Reno</ORGANIZATION> case
in which the group was exonerated of charges that its lyrics prompted a
suicide? -- Judas Priest seems to be alive and kicking.;    The same could be
said of the lovely and talented <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>. <PERSON>Mr. Cooper</PERSON>, to you, baffled critics and
fans and common sense by going platinum with his <DATE>1989</DATE> album, "Trash." It was a
real comeback -- professionally and musically -- with a Gothic rock sound that
was the equal of his classics. He should pull out all the props for this
tour.;    <ORGANIZATION>Motorhead</ORGANIZATION> is Motorhead. If I have to explain that to you, you
probably wouldn't understand anyway. For a decade and much more, this band has
made metal that is an unalloyed pleasure, untarnished by such trivial matters
as good taste and listenability.;    Mixing business and pleasure;  <ORGANIZATION>Metal
Church</ORGANIZATION> and Dangerous Toys haven't got the Big Names -- or the fanciful names
-- of their tour counterparts, but they might be interesting opening acts.;   
All of which makes the business side of this tour all the more annoying.
Operation <ORGANIZATION>Rock &amp; Roll</ORGANIZATION> could be fun and a real deal for the fans. But all the
marketing and promotional tie-ins prove that metal has become as much a
business as a pleasure.;     <ORGANIZATION>Operation Rock &amp; Roll</ORGANIZATION>; When: <TIME>5 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE>;
Where: Shoreline Amphitheater, One Amphitheater Parkway, Mountain View;
Tickets: <MONEY>$22.50</MONEY>/<MONEY>$18.50</MONEY>, (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  HARRY SUMRALL, Mercury News Music Writer  </BYLINE>
