<LEADPARA>  LET'S get to the most important question first: Is there a snake in Alice
Cooper's new act?;    "We do have a new snake for this tour," says Alice,
laughing. "We call him Salt Lake Sidney. He's a Mormon snake. He doesn't drink
coffee and he doesn't work on Sundays."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SCHOOL'S OUT, AND HERE COMES ALICE COOPER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  MUSIC  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Cooper, 43, is calling from <LOCATION>Salt Lake City</LOCATION>, where Operation Rock &amp; Roll
played this week (the show touches down here at <TIME>5 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>Shoreline
Amphitheater</ORGANIZATION>). That explains the snake's name, he says.;    Fans will walk out
changed;    <PERSON>Sidney</PERSON>, it seems, is part of what the all-time master of
theatrical rock describes as "a real <PERSON>Alice Cooper</PERSON> show. We've got a set of our
own, very high-tech, with loads of real oooooo-ahhhh effects. At one point in
the act, we take fans from the crowd and put them on a <LOCATION>Frankenstein</LOCATION> table and
we lift it to the ceiling and when they come out, they're (pause) different.";
   In what way, <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>?;    "I really don't want to give anything away," he
says with another laugh. For such a gothic kind of guy, <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> is downright
upbeat.;    Keep in mind, we are talking about <PERSON>Alice Cooper</PERSON>, he of the
guillotine and black eye makeup and coiling snakes; the man who, in the '70s,
put the shock into rock. Along the way, he recorded a rock classic or two --
"I'm 18," "School's Out" -- and had a comeback platinum record, <DATE>1989</DATE>'s
"Trash.";    What sort of rock fans come to see <PERSON>Alice Cooper</PERSON>, these days?
Young, old or what?;    "I think the older ones come but they mostly sit in
the back. When I look at the crowd from the stage, the ones in the front are
usually about 15. You know, the ones with tattoos and no teeth.";    He's
laughing again.;    It's all about hits;    How has he been able to do it lo
these many years? Alice lowers his voice and gets down to business:;    "It's
about hits. 'I'm 18' is one of those songs that anyone can relate to. The
angst lives on. Theatrics without hits is novelty and that would get boring
after a while. But if you have the theatrics and the hits, that makes a show
with meaning. When we get the effects going and play the hits, we get 10,000
people going 'Oh, wow!' ";    To <PERSON>Alice Cooper</PERSON>, that's no laughing matter.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  HARRY SUMRALL, Mercury News Music Writer  </BYLINE>
