<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Hurt and Farrow: Stuck in an upper-class rut (color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  LIKE her namesake in Wonderland, Woody Allen's Alice finds things becoming
curiouser and curiouser as she tumbles through her own mixed-up life. Unlike
Lewis Carroll's wanderer, Allen's heroine, played by Mia Farrow in the
souffle-airy "Alice," is fully grown and all too willing to play the
proverbial babe in the woods.;    Indeed, her friends refer to her (behind her
back) as "Miss Mouse . . . so trusting."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MIA IN WOODYLAND: MAGIC AND MIRACLES
ALLEN ABANDONS HIS USUAL ANGST FOR A SLIGHT,
SWEET FAIRY TALE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Film Review
See also related story on this page.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     That <PERSON>Allen</PERSON>'s heroine eventually sorts things out -- learns who's
dependable, who's not; what's up, what's down -- is more the result of luck,
coincidence and old-hat legerdemain than any real resourcefulness on her
part.;    <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> is, for all intents and purposes, a surrogate for <ORGANIZATION>Allen</ORGANIZATION>'s
classic schlemiel. She even has that oh-so-; For page 7E;    Woody habit of
whining when no one's listening.;    <ORGANIZATION>Farrow</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>, however, is in a
marvelous state of grace, where much befalls her but nothing does any real
harm. Alice is <PERSON>Allen</PERSON>'sFilm Review; dream-child or cockeyed optimist, someone
who can take the worst that life has to shell out without becoming jaded,
cynical.;    And life does throw <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> a few unexpected curves, including a
smug, philandering husband (<PERSON>William Hurt</PERSON>) and a pack of rich, devious
girlfriends (played by <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Judy Davis</PERSON>, among others).;    "I'm one of
those women who shop all day and have pedicures. I want to do more with my
life," <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> sort of complains.;    <ORGANIZATION>Alice</ORGANIZATION>'s salvation comes during one of her
regular visits to the beauty salon/health spa. That's where she learns about a
<LOCATION>Chinatown</LOCATION> acupuncturist/magician named <PERSON>Dr. Yang</PERSON> (the late <PERSON>Keye Luke</PERSON> of
"Gremlins"). Yang pronounces <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s chronic backache psychosomatic. He
prescribes hypnotism and an assortment of "special herbs." The hypnotism takes
her back to the start of her problems; the herbs have a more extreme effect,
causing her to become completely uninhibited and then -- shades of <PERSON>H.G. Wells</PERSON>!
-- invisible.;    The joke is that the timid-to-transparent <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> is at her
most vital and decisive as the Invisible Woman.;    It's while under another
of <ORGANIZATION>Yang</ORGANIZATION>'s spells that <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> approaches <PERSON>Joe</PERSON>, a jazz musician whose daughter
attends the same kindergarten as <ORGANIZATION>Alice</ORGANIZATION>'s daughter. In this uptown fairy tale's
funniest bit, the usually skittish <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> seduces Joe with every conceivable
saxophone double-entendre. Joe, played by <PERSON>Joe Mantegna</PERSON> of "Godfather III," is
understandably amazed.;    So how are we to take all this? <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> tips us off
with his music, which ranges from <ORGANIZATION>Dixieland</ORGANIZATION> jazz to deliriously romantic
standards (such as "Moonlight Becomes You") to canned studio music. This is
<PERSON>Allen</PERSON> doing a schizoid Noel Coward/naughty satyr routine. Little wonder the
results run the gamut from silly to sardonic.;    Enchanting and almost
frivolous, "Alice" has the feel of <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> on sabbatical from the angst-ridden
types of "<DATE>September</DATE>," "Hannah and Her Sisters," "Another Woman" and, indeed,
the much-overrated "Crimes &amp; Misdemeanors." In tone, <PERSON>Allen</PERSON>'s latest most
closely matches "A <ORGANIZATION>Midsummer Night</ORGANIZATION>'s Sex Comedy" and the director's
contribution to "New York Stories." Like those works, this one is loosely
structured to the point of being haphazard, distracted. In spots, it feels
like <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> taking <PERSON>Dr. Yang</PERSON>'s advice to Alice -- doing whatever feels right at
the moment.;    <PERSON>Allen</PERSON>'s casting is certainly strange. Trading on his status as
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s most individualistic film maker -- the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> <PERSON>Ingmar Bergman</PERSON>, if
you will -- <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> has filled minor roles with such notables as <PERSON>Alec Baldwin</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Cybill Shepherd</PERSON>, <PERSON>Blythe Danner</PERSON>, <PERSON>Gwen Verdon</PERSON> and <PERSON>Bernadette Peters</PERSON>. Baldwin
appears as the ghost of an old beau; <ORGANIZATION>Shepherd</ORGANIZATION> is a suddenly disdainful friend
with a real career; <PERSON>Peters</PERSON> is <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s amusingly bossy muse.;    Talking of
muses, in some respects this is <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> forsaking his inner voice for the voices
of others -- among them, <PERSON>Dickens</PERSON>, <PERSON>Carroll</PERSON>, <PERSON>Preston Sturges</PERSON> and, for a Peter
Pan-inspired joyride over <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>J.M. Barrie.</LOCATION>;    The latter adventure is
the perfect metaphor for this lighter-than-air concoction, which attempts to
sneak up on serious matters about self-worth. The strategy doesn't always
work, as <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> scores his biggest laughs with his most obvious bits (about
bored homemakers and jaded <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> cabbies), but it does make for a pleasant
enough diversion, like a promenade along Fifth Avenue in the fall.;    More,
it gives <PERSON>Farrow</PERSON> her best screen role since "The Purple Rose of <LOCATION>Cairo</LOCATION>." <PERSON>Farrow</PERSON>,
who has never looked lovelier, really comes into her own with this one. Here
finally is the opportunity to show her true range as a comedian, a range that
encompasses screwball antics and a waif-like girlishness.;    <PERSON>Like Alice</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Farrow</PERSON> has been at a crossroads for some time. With her 11th feature with
<PERSON>Allen</PERSON>, the actress commits to a definite path and demonstrates a playful
sexuality that's darn-near irresistible.; <LOCATION>Alice</LOCATION>; (star)(star) 1/2; Rated:
PG-13 (slight profanity); Cast: <PERSON>Mia Farrow</PERSON>, <PERSON>William Hurt</PERSON>, <PERSON>Joe Mantegna</PERSON>;
Director-writer: <PERSON>Woody Allen</PERSON>  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  GLENN LOVELL, Mercury News Film Critic  </BYLINE>
