<DESCRIPT>  DANCE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ALONZO King doesn't abide much by bourgeois affectations such as costumes and
sets for his chamber ballet, Lines Dance Company.;    Its spring season at the
Cowell Theater was as austere as it could be: four abstract works in
more-or-less flesh-colored unitards, assisted only by Wendy W. Gilmore's
delicate lighting.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  KING OF SUBTLETY
LINES DOES FINE WITH GREAT MUSIC, DANCE;
'ADVENTURES OF ALICE' OFF TO A GOOD START  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Dance Reviews  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     King is a talented maverick who does what he wants, his way, without paying
much attention to the questions of marketing and audience appeal that bedevil
most arts organizations. So what if all my pieces look alike? he seems to
shrug. They're not.;    The subtle distinctions between them are organic,
coming directly out of the music, which is invariably ambitious, unusual and
sophisticated. This program featured off-the-beaten-track <PERSON>Bach</PERSON>; <PERSON>Donald
Fontowitz</PERSON>, a frequent collaborator; and <PERSON>Charles Valentin Alkan</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Sofia
Gubaidulina</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Bohuslav Martinu</PERSON> -- not exactly household names but all makers
of wondrous music.;    "Without Wax" (<DATE>1990</DATE>), made for BalletMet of <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION>, is a very special work, and its title says a great deal about King. It
comes from a custom in Roman times, when sculptors signed their work "sine
cereus" to show that no artificial smootheners were used to disguise nicks,
flaws and cracks. It's an indication of integrity, though it may leave the art
looking grainy or rough-hewn.;    So with the piece. King's company has strong
women and weak men, but he presents all proudly: These are his dancers; take
them for all in all.;    Much of it is danced to silence, which demands great
ensemble awareness and instinct; the silvery, thin, celestial streaks of
"Rejoice for Violin and Cello" by <ORGANIZATION>Gubaidulina</ORGANIZATION>, a contemporary Soviet composer,
are less musical background than evocative sound effects. There's an
invocation for men, a response for the women, a finale for all; and at the
center, a sumptuous pas de deux for <PERSON>Summer Lee Rhatigan</PERSON> and <PERSON>Gregory Dawson</PERSON>,
set to a heart-breaking score by <PERSON>Martinu</PERSON> (1890-1952).;    The program also
included revivals of "Toccata in D minor" (<DATE>1990</DATE>), the duet from "Alkan"
(<DATE>1989</DATE>), by far the best section of <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s one-act homage to the eccentric
French pianist and composer (1813-88); and "Awake in the Dream," made for
<LOCATION>Sacramento Ballet</LOCATION> in <DATE>1988.</DATE>;    The last is a post-apocalyptic dreamscape for a
single woman in blue (<ORGANIZATION>Katherine Warner</ORGANIZATION>) and a heartless group who turn on her.
King seems determined not to give us any clues about the internal narrative,
and the ballet's edge of menace is somewhat dulled by his elliptical
story-telling.;    <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Balletland</LOCATION>; "The Adventures of Alice," the
ambitious new <DATE>spring</DATE> production of <ORGANIZATION>San Jose Dance Theater</ORGANIZATION>, is the start of a
wonderful children's ballet. Only the start, mind you, but a good healthy
one.;    This immense work -- 120 dancers, 160 costumes, seven flexible
set-pieces called periaktoi (their origin is in Hellenic theater), lights and
fog, a commissioned score for 11 instrumentalists, vocal quartet and
electronics -- was put together in just three months. This in itself is a
miracle. Getting the bugs out can be left for next year, for the company would
like to make "Alice" an annual event, on the order of "Nutcracker.";    More
words;  Right now, it badly needs a libretto, and probably a voiceover
narrator. What has been created by choreographer <PERSON>Jody White</PERSON>, a dance teacher
from <LOCATION>Fairfax</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION>, is not so much "The Adventures of Alice" as
"Episodes From 'Alice.' " There are a few scenes and characters from "Alice in
<LOCATION>Wonderland</LOCATION>," but the bulk of the ballet is taken from the less familiar
"Through the Looking-Glass.";    I would be tempted to scrub the "Alice"
sections entirely and expand the piece into a "Looking-Glass" ballet, except
the noble polonaise for the <ORGANIZATION>Gryphon</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Mock Turtle</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> is very
beautiful and, moreover, the high point of composer <PERSON>Henry Mollicone</PERSON>'s charming
score.;    In rehearsal, to help the dancers (<PERSON>Jennifer Larsen</PERSON> as the <ORGANIZATION>Gryphon</ORGANIZATION>
and <PERSON>Griffin Dong</PERSON> as the Mock Turtle) establish the proper mood, White was
inspired to say, "Think of the <ORGANIZATION>Gryphon</ORGANIZATION> as an endangered species." They caught
on immediately, and the dance is fragile and wistful, steps from a bygone
era.;    White's most effective device is to have <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> (15-year-old <PERSON>Sharon
Wehner</PERSON>) end the ballet by leaving the stage and opening one of the exit doors
of the house, where golden sunlight streams in, returning her to reality.;   
Other good episodes are "Jabberwocky," featuring <PERSON>David Roxander</PERSON>, White's son,
a former principal dancer with the <ORGANIZATION>National Ballet of Canada</ORGANIZATION>, as the <PERSON>Beamish</PERSON>
Boy; the war of the chess pieces, accomplished by strobe lights and the
harmless but showy explosions of flash pots; and the Queen of Hearts' garden,
where the white roses are painted red by the gardening staff.;    On the down
side, there are a lot of terrific costumes wasted on characters who barely
appear, such as the Mad Hatter, the <DATE>March Hare</DATE> and the Dormouse. And the
senior dancers of the company dribble by in a floral episode that has nothing
to do with the story.;    When I saw the piece at dress rehearsal, it was
severely overcast by machine-made fog, and the lights, by <PERSON>Brad Belleville</PERSON>,
were prosaic. Some of these problems may have been corrected for the
performances; if not, there's always next year.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  JUDITH GREEN, Mercury News Dance Writer  </BYLINE>
