<HEAD>James, Elizabeth Most Popular Names for 1989 British Babies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James and <PERSON>Elizabeth</PERSON>, the names of British kings
and queens, were the most popular names for babies born in <DATE>1989</DATE>,
according to the social editor of the Times of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> newspaper.
   Of the 2,780 boys whose births were announced in the newspaper
last year, 392 had <PERSON>James</PERSON> as one of their names, 120 ahead of the
runner-up, <LOCATION>William</LOCATION>, said social editor <PERSON>Helen Beard</PERSON>.
   Of the 2,645 birth announcements for girls, 254 had <LOCATION>Elizabeth</LOCATION>
among their names, 106 ahead of the second most popular choice,
<LOCATION>Charlotte</LOCATION>, she said.
   Of the first names chosen, <PERSON>James</PERSON> was also the most popular for
boys, as it has been every year since <DATE>1964</DATE>, <PERSON>Ms. Beard</PERSON> wrote in her
annual letter to the editor outlining parents' selections. James
was followed by <PERSON>Thomas</PERSON>, <PERSON>William</PERSON>, <PERSON>Alexander</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Edward</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Charles</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Oliver</PERSON>, <PERSON>George</PERSON>, <PERSON>Robert</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Henry</ORGANIZATION>.
   Elizabeth was only the 10th most popular choice as a first name
for girls, the newspaper reported. Charlotte was the top choice, a
position acquired in <DATE>1983</DATE> but surrendered to <LOCATION>Emma</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> in <DATE>1987</DATE>
and <DATE>1988</DATE> respectively.
   Charlotte was followed by <PERSON>Emily</PERSON>, <PERSON>Sophie</PERSON>, <PERSON>Emma</PERSON>, <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Olivia</LOCATION>,
<PERSON>Alexandra</PERSON>, <PERSON>Katherine</PERSON>, Lucy and then <LOCATION>Elizabeth</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> has had two queens named <LOCATION>Elizabeth</LOCATION>, including the
current monarch, <PERSON>Elizabeth II</PERSON>, and two <LOCATION>King James</LOCATION>. William, <LOCATION>Edward</LOCATION>,
<PERSON>Charles</PERSON>, <PERSON>George</PERSON>, <PERSON>Henry</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Charlotte</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> and <PERSON>Alexandra</PERSON> are also
names associated with the royal family past and present.
</TEXT>
