<CAPTION>  Photos (4); PHOTO: David Lee Roth, so popular in past years, had to cancel his
summer tour because of poor ticket sales.; PHOTO: Alice Cooper; ... Bad draw;
PHOTO: The bearded boys of ZZ Top, who performed to a sold-out crowd at San
Jose's Spartan Stadium in August, were among the few winners in this poor rock
'n' roll season, with the second-highest grossing tour after the Grateful Dead
(color).; PHOTO: This season's popular Lollapalooza tour, headlined by Jane's
Addiction, above, sold out two shows at Shoreline, but other tours featuring
such acts as Sisters of Mercy, Public Enemy, Judas Priest and Alice Cooper
haven't fared well (color).  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  ENTERTAINMENT; TREND; RELATION; ECONOMY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  AS THE Labor Day Weekend rolls through and the summer rock season rolls out,
the receipts have been tabulated and the winners are: the Grateful Dead, the
Lollapalooza tour and rap/dance music in general.;   But the big news was the
losers, which included just about everyone else.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GROUPS ARE PLAYING TO EMPTY STADIUMS -- OR STAYING
HOME  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Entertainment and the Recession; See also related stories on pages 17, 24, 25
of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The old geezers in the Dead topped the national mid-year revenue totals
with <MONEY>$22.6 million</MONEY>. Dominating the local concert scene, the 21-city, nine-act
Lollapalooza tour -- headlined by <PERSON>Jane</PERSON>'s Addiction -- and the <ORGANIZATION>KMEL Summer</ORGANIZATION> Jam
rap/dance spectacular sold out two shows apiece at Mountain View's Shoreline
Amphitheatre.;   But these few successes were eclipsed by the stunning decline
in the business itself. The Fresno-based concert business publication Pollstar
listed mid-year revenues for the Top 100 shows at <MONEY>$76 million</MONEY>, down by <PERCENT>30
percent</PERCENT> from the record <MONEY>$110 million</MONEY> of 1990.;   One of the most highly touted
tours at the start of the pop <DATE>summer</DATE> season was one that included the <ORGANIZATION>Sisters
of Mercy</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Public Enemy</ORGANIZATION> and Gang of Four. But when the <LOCATION>West Coast</LOCATION> leg of that
tour was canceled because of poor ticket sales, its title, "The Tune In, Turn
On, Burn Out Tour," came to symbolize the state of the rock concert business.
In <DATE>1991</DATE>, the fans did tune in and turn on, but they didn't turn out in the
record-smashing numbers of the past.;   Other touring "festivals" of the
season didn't fare much better. Operation Rock And Roll (Judas Priest, <PERSON>Alice
Cooper</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Motorhead</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Metal Church</ORGANIZATION> and Dangerous Toys) drew barely 5,500 fans to
the 20,000-seat Shoreline Amphitheatre in <DATE>July</DATE> (in <DATE>1990</DATE>, <LOCATION>Judas Priest</LOCATION> drew
13,000 fans to a show in <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION>) and did the same poor business in other
parts of the country. And the nostalgia-infused Gathering of the Tribes II,
with nine acts including <ORGANIZATION>Fishbone</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Primus</LOCATION>, drew 7,000 to <LOCATION>Shoreline</LOCATION>; its
tour was canceled after three shows.;   <PERSON>David Lee Roth</PERSON>, who had sold out the
<ORGANIZATION>Cow Palace</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Daly City</LOCATION> in past years, was forced to cancel his <DATE>summer</DATE> tour
because of disappointing ticket receipts.;   And while the Guns N' Roses tour
has done well in many venues (the group sold out its two-night stand at
<LOCATION>Shoreline</LOCATION>), it hasn't done sellout business in several of the cities where two
shows were scheduled -- a major disappointment given the group's stature in
the scene.;   <ORGANIZATION>Pollstar</ORGANIZATION> editor <PERSON>Gary Bongiovanni</PERSON> cites several factors in the
poor showing of various tours and venues: the recession; competition from
other forms of entertainment; and a continuing trend of escalating ticket
prices.;   "This is the first time that a recession has adversely affected the
business," he says. "And with fewer entertainment dollars out there, these
shows have had to compete with movies like 'Terminator 2' and with places like
<LOCATION>Great America</LOCATION> and with activities like going to the beach. It's been a rough
year.";   He also notes that for the first time the business has seen
"resistance on the part of the fans to escalating prices" of tickets, which
have gone up <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> from <DATE>1990.</DATE>;   <LOCATION>The Bay Area</LOCATION> has suffered a decline in
business (although it hasn't been affected as much as other parts of the
country, particularly the <LOCATION>Northeast</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Midwest</LOCATION>).;   Promoter <PERSON>Bill Graham</PERSON>,
whose <PERSON>Bill Graham</PERSON> Presents books <PERSON>Shoreline Amphitheatre</PERSON>, said business at that
venue was off approximately <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>15 percent</PERCENT> so far this year. "But
while our business hasn't been as good as in previous years it wasn't that
bad. We're like a baseball player who usually hits .400 and is now hitting
.350 this season.";   While <PERSON>Graham</PERSON> also blames the recession, he said there
haven't been as many shows on the touring circuit. "In <DATE>1990</DATE> we did 58 shows at
Shoreline," he said, "but this year we did 45.";   Given the decline in the
concert business, many groups were reluctant to tour during the usually prime
<DATE>summer</DATE> season. Acts such as Queen and R.E.M. released new records (R.E.M.'s
"Out of Time" was No. 1 on the charts at one point) but declined to tour. And
acts such as Dire Straits and New Kids on the Block postponed tours they had
initially scheduled for the <DATE>summer</DATE> because of the dreary commercial climate.; 
 The absence of the stadium tours by the usual blockbuster names was also
partly to blame for the season's poor showing. In past years, seasonal
revenues have been bolstered by the stadium tours of such acts as U2, <PERSON>Bruce
Springsteen</PERSON> and <PERSON>Paul McCartney</PERSON>. But this season the only consistent stadium
draw was the Grateful Dead, which averaged approximately 47,000 tickets per
show. (Those bewhiskered galoots of ZZ Top, who had the second-highest
grossing tour at mid-year with revenues of <MONEY>$18.5 million</MONEY>, did divert from
their arena tour to play a sold-out show at <LOCATION>Spartan Stadium</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> <DATE>Aug.
10</DATE>.);   But if the blockbuster acts haven't been present in this <DATE>summer</DATE> pop
season, blockbuster ticket prices have. <PERSON>Graham</PERSON> says the responsibility for
that resides with the artists.;   "One of the misconceptions on the part of
the fans," <PERSON>Graham</PERSON> says, "is that it is the promoter who establishes the prices
of tickets. But those are predicated by the amount that the acts are charging.
If an act decides to charge, hypothetically, <MONEY>$200,000</MONEY> (to perform), I have to
adjust what we are charging for tickets. Any time that an act is willing to
play for less, I will charge less.";   Is he saying the acts are greedy?;  
"When it comes to the ticket prices," <PERSON>Graham</PERSON> said, "the superstars could care
less" about the fans.;   But with fans resisting those prices, <PERSON>Graham</PERSON> thinks
there could be an upside to all of this. "I think the poor showings of these
tours might force them to rethink what they will charge.";   A few of the
tours, such as the one that came with Damn Yankees and Bad Company, lowered
their ticket prices and, Pollstar reports, ended up making as much money as
other tours while performing to vastly greater numbers of fans. And with one
of the primary roles of tours being record promotion, that arguably translates
to wiser  career enhancement. (But even that did not work out for <ORGANIZATION>Roth</ORGANIZATION>, who
lowered the ticket prices to <MONEY>$9</MONEY> for lawn seats at his various "shed" shows.); 
 "It's been a wacky year," <PERSON>Bongiovanni</PERSON> says. "But the business is cyclical and
it looks as if the latter part of the year and the next year should improve.";
  At this point, demand for tickets for a tour by the consistently
best-selling Van <PERSON>Halen</PERSON> (which comes to the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION> <DATE>Sept. 13-14</DATE>) has been
relatively heavy. And other acts that are set to begin tours include <PERSON>Tom
Petty</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Prince</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Paula Abdul</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Luther Vandross</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Bob Seger</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Metallica</ORGANIZATION>. And
there is speculation that U2 and <PERSON>Springsteen</PERSON> could be touring in <DATE>1992.</DATE>;   But
at the moment, until these heavy-hitters hit the circuit, all the business can
do is tend its wounds and hope that the recession and its woes will go away.
(box)  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  HARRY SUMRALL, Mercury News Music Writer  </BYLINE>
