<DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE love that illuminates "Wildflower," a hauntingly beautiful movie on
cable's Lifetime channel Tuesday at 9 p.m., flows through it like sunlight
through stained glass.;   The tale, set in rural Depression-era Georgia and
directed by actress Diane Keaton, has the timelessness of a parable. It's
almost biblical in its simplicity.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DIANE KEATON'S LATEST STARRING ROLE: DIRECTOR  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     <PERSON>Patricia Arquette</PERSON> stars as a beautiful, neglected 17-year-old girl
imprisoned by her wicked stepfather because she is "touched by the devil" --
deaf and epileptic.;   <PERSON>Reese Witherspoon</PERSON> plays 13-year-old <PERSON>Ellie Perkins</PERSON>, a
neighbor who discovers the grimy, half-wild girl locked away in a chicken
coop. She is unwashed, illiterate, and barely capable of speech.;   <PERSON>Ellie</PERSON> and
her 18-year-old brother, <PERSON>Sammy</PERSON> (<PERSON>William McNamara</PERSON>), befriend <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>, against the
vehement wishes of their father, <PERSON>Jack</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>Beau Bridges</ORGANIZATION>, in a masterly
performance), a widower still locked in his grief.;   They help <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> emerge
from her ignorance and isolation, and when conflict looms with <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s father,
papa <PERSON>Jack</PERSON> is forced out of his own emotional isolation.;   At the same time,
young <PERSON>Sammy</PERSON> realizes that his unsophisticated friend is rapidly becoming a
beautiful woman, and he doesn't quite know what to make of his feelings.;  
<PERSON>Sara Flanigan</PERSON>'s script, based on her books, treats these kinds of love with
great feeling and without a trace of greeting-card sentimentality.;   Here is
the unselfish love of humankind; here is redemptive love; here is familial
love (as well as its cancerous absence); and here, happily and unhappily, is
the love of a man and a woman.;   <ORGANIZATION>Arquette</ORGANIZATION>'s portrayal of a profoundly
hearing-impaired girl is utterly believable. According to production notes,
she researched the role by listening to speech tapes of hearing-impaired
children before and after cochlear implants. She also worked with a speech
therapist, and was coached by a girl who has a hearing loss similar to
<ORGANIZATION>Alice's</ORGANIZATION>.;   "Wildflower" is a superb movie, a fully realized, sophisticated
piece of film-making. But try telling that to its director, and you can
practically hear her blush over the telephone.;   Although the movie is billed
as director <PERSON>Keaton</PERSON>'s first dramatic feature, she demurred at calling
"Wildflower" a movie.;   "I don't see it as a film, I see it as a television
show," she said. "You have to plan the whole movie according to these
breaks.";   To ease the transition shock, <PERSON>Keaton</PERSON> designed thematic "bumpers,"
which show <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s lovely eyes against a background of lush, red wildflowers.;
  She consciously set about saturating the production with green and red
tones.;   "I didn't want to see much blue, because I felt like I wanted to
just sink into this world of green, and being caught up in the woods, and the
romance of that," she said. "I wanted to be hidden under green.";   <PERSON>Keaton</PERSON>,
who has directed a documentary, "Heaven," and episodes of <ORGANIZATION>ABC</ORGANIZATION>'s "<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> Beach"
and "Twin Peaks," was reluctant to discuss her contribution to the film,
praising her cast and collaborators. "I got lucky on this," she said.;   And
she wants to do more directing.;   "The problem with acting is sitting in a
trailer, and being left to your own devices and thoughts and fantasies and
self-obsessions, and all the things that are terrifying about acting," she
said.;   "With directing it's a different kind of terror. You don't have time
to think about your terror as much. You don't have time to contemplate about
all the horrible accidents of what you're doing.";   "When you're acting, it's
an interior adventure that's about feelings and anticipations. And I kind of
am more afraid of that, in a strange way," she said. "In terms of using my
feelings and my emotional life, I really feel like acting is, in a way,
harder."  </TEXT>
