in 'Strangers in Good Company.'  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  ELDERLY; WOMEN; TRIP; MOVIE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IT'S the start of a thousand typical movies. A bus with eight women breaks
down in the middle of the woods. Night is falling. There's only a deserted
house for shelter. Is this a chain-saw I see before me?;   But "Strangers in
Good Company" (playing at the Towne, through Thursday) isn't a typical movie.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THERE'S GOOD COMPANY ON THIS WAYWARD BUS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  MOVIES; REVIEW  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     For one thing, the average age of the stranded passengers is about 70. For
another, the closest thing to violence is the barbecuing of a couple of fish.
And the only scene remotely resembling nudity comes when three of the women
take off their shoes and wade in a pond.;   "Strangers in Good Company" isn't
a horror film, or even a Hollywood movie. It's a Canadian character study of
seven passengers and their young bus driver, who have to flee a wayward bus in
search of aid. Along the way they find themselves, and help each other.;  
There are a few moments of humor, some singing, and practical information on
fixing bus engines with emery boards and catching fish with pantyhose. Mostly
there's talk.;   And talk. And more talk, broken only by periods of
introspection. Those who sat stunned through "The Whales of <DATE>August</DATE>" may have a
strange feeling of deja vu as one old woman after another looks off across a
misty body of water and sighs. Others may want to storm the screen by the end
and help these people fix their bus. Please, somebody -- get them home so we
can go home.;   But if you can slow yourself down to the film's pace, there
are other charms. The movie is full of overlapping dialogue and casually
observed moments. It plays a little like a documentary. And in a way, it is.; 
 Director <PERSON>Cynthia Scott</PERSON> decided to let the women in the film -- all non-actors
-- use their own first names and tell bits of their own stories. The
photographs intercut through their monologues are pictures of them. And
although there was a script, the pains and memories they reveal are theirs,
too.;   Knowing that going into the film makes it more powerful. Seeing it
unprepared, the movie seems a little contrived and politically correct. One
woman (<PERSON>Alice Diablo</PERSON>) is a Mohawk Indian, the bus driver (<PERSON>Michelle Sweeney</PERSON>) is
black, another passenger (<PERSON>Catherine Roche</PERSON>) is a nun. It's a little like the
<ORGANIZATION>Rainbow Coalition</ORGANIZATION> on a day trip.;   But once you realize the fact behind the
fiction, the film begins to work. <PERSON>Beth Webber</PERSON>, who confesses to a frail vanity
about the lines in her neck, really does worry about looking old. <PERSON>Mary Meigs</PERSON>,
who talks of her once-secret life as a lesbian, did come out of the closet at
age 60. These aren't just characters; they're real people, and the movie is an
artful kind of eavesdropping.;   Moreover, the film has a pointed message:
Growing old doesn't mean giving up. These women are involved, political,
funny, bawdy. And although they talk about men, they're not dependent on them.
They're perfectly able to take care of themselves, even in their 80s, even
stranded in the woods.;   "We're alive," they shout at one moment in unison.
"We're alive." And it isn't so much a call for help as it is a simple,
triumphant statement.; Strangers in Good Company; (star)(star)(star); Rated:
PG; Cast: <PERSON>Alice Diablo</PERSON>, <PERSON>Mary Meigs</PERSON>, <PERSON>Catherine Roche</PERSON>, <PERSON>Michelle Sweeney</PERSON>;
Director: <PERSON>Cynthia Scott</PERSON>; Writer: <PERSON>Scott</PERSON>, <PERSON>Gloria Demers</PERSON>; Running Time: 1 hour,
40 minutes  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  STEPHEN WHITTY, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE>
