<HEAD>Neighbors Wonder if Missing Boa is Hungry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Alice is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NOVI, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alice, the 8-foot boa constrictor, hasn't
been home since <DATE>last weekend</DATE> and neighbors are wondering _ is Alice
getting hungry?
   Alice normally eats once a week and it's been that long since
the male snake's last meal, a rat, said Deputy Police Chief <PERSON>Richard
Faulkner</PERSON>.
   ``You know what it's going to do out there. It's going to
grow,'' said <PERSON>Carole Stevens</PERSON>, whose cat is locked inside until Alice
turns up.
   Alice got loose after a friend of its owner took it outside <DATE>last
Saturday</DATE>, police said. The friend fell asleep and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> slithered
away.
   ``I saw these two people outside looking in my trees. I thought
maybe they lost a bird,'' said <PERSON>Stevens</PERSON>, who lives near snake owner
<PERSON>Linda Pyorala</PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION>Country Cousin Mobile Home Village</ORGANIZATION>. When
<PERSON>Stevens</PERSON> learned <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> was missing, she called police.
   Pyorala declined to comment about her missing boa.
</TEXT>
