<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Colors'' and ``White Mischief''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``COLORS''
   
   ``Colors'' marks the return of <PERSON>Dennis Hopper</PERSON> to directing, and
that should have been news in itself.
   His <DATE>1969</DATE> ``Easy Rider'' changed the face of the Hollywood film
industry forever, then <ORGANIZATION>Hopper</ORGANIZATION> fell from grace. After two decades of
drugs and booze, he turned his life around and returned as an actor
of remarkable depth.
   Reportedly the insistence of <PERSON>Sean Penn</PERSON> resulted in <LOCATION>Hopper</LOCATION>'s
chance to direct again. A good thing. ``Colors'' reveals <PERSON>Hopper</PERSON> as
a filmmaker of great skill, though a glimmer remains of the
indulgences that contributed to his downfall.
   As a director of action, <ORGANIZATION>Hopper</ORGANIZATION> is superlative. Just when you
think you had seen every kind of car chase, he provides one through
the streets and back alleys of <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> that is truly
breathtaking. And a fugitive's rampage through a crowded
restaurant, pursued by <LOCATION>Penn</LOCATION>, is a kinetic wonder.
   On the downside, <PERSON>Hopper</PERSON> betrays his existential tendencies,
staging confrontational scenes that have no real motivation or
payoff. This partly may be due to <PERSON>Michael Schiffer</PERSON>'s rather
formless script.
   <LOCATION>Penn</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Duvall</PERSON> are unlikely partners on the gang war scene.
<PERSON>Duvall</PERSON> is nearing retirement, a cool head who tries to establish a
rapport with gang members. Penn is hotheaded and himself prone to
violence. Both try to act as <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> peacemakers in the growing war
between the ``Bloods'' and the ``Cripps.''
   ``Colors'' manages to portray the gang members as human beings
not senseless criminals. Penn, who may be the <PERSON>Brando</PERSON> of his
generation, continues his string of impressive performances, and
<PERSON>Duvall</PERSON> performs with his usual authority. <PERSON>Maria Conchita Alonso</PERSON> is
wasted as the obligatory love interest.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Orion</ORGANIZATION> release was produced by <PERSON>Robert H. Solo</PERSON> and scored with
fine, thumping style by <PERSON>Herbie Hancock</PERSON>. The R rating is well
deserved because of the street language, violence, nudity and sex
scenes. Running time: 2 hours.
   _ By <PERSON>Bob Thomas</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Associated Press Writer</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
