of memorable tunes himself. Forget all those great interpretations
of ``Goodnight Irene,'' ``Amazing Grace,'' ``Stealin''' and ``This
Land Is Your Land'' that you've heard him do over the years. Don't
even think about ``Alice's Restaurant,'' that epic tale of youthful
rebellion and anti-war protest.
   What <PERSON>Arlo Guthrie</PERSON> really wanted to be was a newspaper reporter.
   ``Yeah, there must be a repressed reporter in one of my hidden
personalities because I love to write,'' laughs <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON>, whose
musical career has seen him evolve from the '60s-kid protest singer
with a sense of humor to one of the pre-eminent voices in American
folk music.
   But he says, ``I didn't become a folk singer because I wanted to
be. I ended up doing this because I didn't know how to do anything
else.
   ``And that hasn't changed much,'' he adds with that quick,
good-natured laugh that his fans have heard so often over the
years. It's the one that sometimes surfaces right on stage, in the
middle of a song, when something strikes him so funny that he has
to stop and tell everyone about it.
   But now the funny stories, the wry asides, the general
observations on the oddities of life are as apt to go down on paper
as over a microphone in a concert hall.
   The ones that are written go into <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON>'s newsletter, The
Rolling Blunder Review, an espistle written in a style that evokes
rollicking images of the kind of old-time journalism chronicled in
such movies as ``The Front Page.''
   But the newsletter never started out to be a newsletter.
   ``It sort of came about by accident,'' <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON> says.
   In the mid-'70s he began collecting addresses of people who
might want a schedule of his shows, but he never really got around
to sending them one.
   ``People started asking us, `When are you going to send us
something?' They'd say, `I signed up 14 times and I never got
anything,''' he recalled.
   So with a great sense of guilt, <ORGANIZATION>The Rolling Blunder Review</ORGANIZATION> was
born. <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON>Jackie</PERSON>, typed it on a single sheet of
paper, made copies and mailed it from their home in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Mass</LOCATION>. Early issues contained only the long-sought schedule and a
few funny comments on ``Alice's Restaurant'' and other songs.
   But as word spread, the newsletter grew. Five years later, it's
an eight-page quarterly, containing stories, letters to the editor
and information on how to buy <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON>'s albums, T-shirts and other
merchandise. There's even a cooking column by <PERSON>Alice Brock</PERSON>. (``You
remember <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>. There's a song about Alice.'')
   Some 60,000 to 70,000 people pay <MONEY>$3</MONEY> a year for it, although it
goes free to people in hospitals and prisons.
   Among the stories in recent issues are reports on concerts to
benefit the environment and in support of student protests in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>
and elsewhere. But somehow, almost everything, no matter how
serious, comes out funny. Sort of like an <PERSON>Arlo Guthrie</PERSON> concert.
   He notes that one role of a folk singer is to comment on
political events of the day as his father, <PERSON>Pete Seeger</PERSON>, <PERSON>Joan Baez</PERSON>
and so many others have done.
   ``But it's not the only job, and it may not even be the most
important job,'' he said. ``The most important thing, for me
personally, is maintaining a sense of humor in an often-humorless
world.''
   For <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON>, the laughs have been frequent. Only he, for
example, could show us (in ``Alice's Restaurant'') how to use a
litterbug arrest as a reason to stay out of the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> during the
<LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> War. Only he has dared speculate (in ``The Pause of Mr
Claus'') that <LOCATION>Santa Claus</LOCATION> might enter houses late at night because
he's a dope fiend. Or that a delightful folk ditty about the joys
of tilling the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> (``The Garden Song'') should be played
backward in search of evil messages.
   The laughs have been so frequent that they've allowed some to
overlook the musical talent. Guthrie is more than proficient on
guitar, piano, harmonica and banjo, as well as a singer of some
range and a writer whose best songs evoke strong images of joy and
sometimes sorrow.
   ``Alice's Restaurant'' started it all in <DATE>1967</DATE>, making him an
overnight star at age 20.
   ``Who could have ever imagined it,'' he says of the way the
youth culture embraced his 18-minute, guitar-accompanied monologue
on how he used a Thanksgiving Day arrest to stay out of the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>.
The song also helped him escape early comparisons with a legendary
father.
   And although <PERSON>Guthrie</PERSON> has almost always included a <PERSON>Woody Guthrie</PERSON>
song or two in his concert repertoire, he downplays the father-son
connection.
   ``For whatever cosmic reasons - and who really understands those
things - I ended up similar to my dad in some ways,'' he says.
``But we're vastly different in other ways.''
   But the connection also brings up another inevitable question.
<PERSON>Woody Guthrie</PERSON> died in <DATE>1967</DATE> of the debilitating neurological
disorder <LOCATION>Huntington</LOCATION>'s Chorea. It has a 50-50 chance of being passed
from parent to child, it strikes in middle age, and <PERSON>Arlo Guthrie</PERSON> is
43.
   But he dismisses such inquiries good-naturedly. ``I'm not dead
yet,'' he says. ``Does that answer your question?''
   He is also not through working yet, continuing to tour regularly
and making plans to record again after several years without a new
album.
   ``I've written some new songs,'' he says. ``I've got enough for
a totally new record.''
   He's also thinking about an animated version for children of
``Alice's Restaurant,'' which was made into a movie in <DATE>1969</DATE>.
   ``It would focus more on the Thanksgiving part and less on the
littering and draft parts,'' he says.
   He notes that the idea of dumping ``a half a ton of garbage'' by
the side of the road isn't as popular as it once was, even if the
dump was closed on Thanksgiving and you'd ``never heard of a dump
closed on Thanksgiving before.''
   ``Littering isn't such a good idea anymore,'' he says a bit
sheepishly. But then he adds with that quick laugh: ``I sure had a
lot of fun on that day though.'
</TEXT>
