<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     <PERSON>Fisher</PERSON>, who's also producing the show, says that only her mother and <PERSON>Andrea
Martin</PERSON>, as the daughter, remain from the original cast. "We're looking around
now for actors to play the grandmother, granddaughter, grandson and
boyfriend." They're now hoping for a midseason berth for the show.;  
REAL-LIFE DRAMA: As new developments unfold in the <DATE>1963</DATE> murder case of civil
rights leader <PERSON>Medgar Evers</PERSON>, producer-director <PERSON>Thomas Carter</PERSON> is preparing to
bring the saga to the small screen.;   The Emmy-winning former "Equal Justice"
producer reports he's in negotiations with <PERSON>Evers</PERSON>' widow, <PERSON>Myrlie Evers</PERSON>, for
rights to her version of the drama -- which may well end with a trial for
suspect Byron De Labeckwith. "She was very active in trying to get the case
reopened," <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> notes, "and she was deeply involved as the authorities
uncovered the new information that allowed them to reopen it." <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> intends
to have the story ready to roll as soon as the case is resolved. He says he
hopes "there will be a trial, and it'll be conclusive." He predicts, "It'll
probably be this <DATE>fall</DATE> . . . early next year at the latest.";   NO GHOUL LIKE
AN OLD GHOUL: <PERSON>Alice Cooper</PERSON>'s living up to his showman reputation. The veteran
rocker is hitting the road on a 12-city concert trek being dubbed "The
Nightmare on Your Street Tour," in which he'll play surprise gigs in surprise
places -- parking lots, warehouse rooftops, and record stores and other
oddball locales that do not include any halls or arenas. His future
appearances are being kept under wraps. We can tell you his next concert is
set to take place somewhere in <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> <DATE>Sept. 2</DATE>. Tour planners also hope to
arrange a playdate by <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> and his band in the middle of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s Times
Square mid-September -- to tie in to the <DATE>Friday</DATE> the 13th opening of "Nightmare
on Elm Street 6," in which <ORGANIZATION>Cooper</ORGANIZATION> is featured.; From <PERSON>Liz Smith</PERSON> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>;
INTERNATIONAL GOODWILL: The most thrilled diva to emerge unscathed from
Hurricane <PERSON>Bob was Beverly Sills</PERSON>, who has been summering in <LOCATION>Martha</LOCATION>'s Vineyard.
Sills left the island to rush to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> this week to meet British Prime
Minister <PERSON>John Major</PERSON> and his wife, confirmed opera lovers, who commanded her
presence. It all happened in the African Room at the <ORGANIZATION>Kennedy Center</ORGANIZATION> with the
<PERSON>William Cheneys</PERSON> and others equally grand -- such as the British ambassador and
Lady Renwick -- in attendance. Then everybody trooped in to see "Phantom of
the Opera" for the umpteenth time.; WEDDING BELLS: Singer <PERSON>Rick Derringer</PERSON> will
marry his back-up singer, <PERSON>Diane Buckie</PERSON>, <DATE>Sunday</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. The happy event
will take place during the intermission of <ORGANIZATION>Derringer</ORGANIZATION>'s concert on Pier 42.
Songwriter <PERSON>B.J. Schapiro</PERSON> will be best man.  </TEXT>
