<HEAD>Alice Faye's Memories of a Bygone Era</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was a time when <PERSON>Alice Faye</PERSON> was queen of
the <ORGANIZATION>20th Century Fox</ORGANIZATION> musicals.
   ``It was great, it was glamorous, it was wonderful. I don't
spend too much time thinking about it, but when I do, it was
lovely. I had so many nice friends, people who were good to me. I
didn't have too many beefs, many complaints,'' she said.
   ``I have great memories _ of the working people. Wonderful stars
like <PERSON>Don Ameche</PERSON>, <PERSON>John Payne</PERSON>, <PERSON>Tyrone Power</PERSON>, <PERSON>Jack Oakie</PERSON>, <PERSON>Jack Haley</PERSON>,
on and on. We had so much fun, we really did. They don't seem to
have that kind of fun today.''
   Now she has produced a book, ``Growing Old, Staying Young''
(<PERSON>E.P. Dutton</PERSON>, <MONEY>$18.95</MONEY>), written with <PERSON>Dick Kleiner</PERSON>. Still a striking
blonde at 75, she also has been spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION>Pfizer
Pharmaceuticals</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``I go out every month, almost,'' she says. ``I travel a day, I
rest a day, then I work two days and I come home. It works out real
nice. It's kind of fun; it keeps me active, keeps me involved and
keeps me off the street.''
   Her book contains the message Faye imparts to her audiences,
whom she calls ``young elders.'' The Faye method:
   ``1. Staying active and involved.
   ``2. Eating a well-balanced diet.
   ``3. No smoking, which is tough for a lot of people.
   ``4. Exercising; that's a key: walking, swimming, stretching.
   ``5. Seeing your doctor and talking to him about your problems.
   ``I throw in 6. Please God, have a sense of humor, because it
helps.''
   She enjoys meeting fans who recall her films of the <DATE>'30s</DATE> and
<DATE>'40s</DATE>. ``All of them have a story to tell you _ they had a baby at
the time I did this movie or I sang that song,'' she said.
   Faye was born <PERSON>Alice Jeanne Leppert</PERSON>, daughter of a <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>
police officer. A teen-age beauty who danced in the Capitol Theater
chorus at 14, she eventually made her way to <ORGANIZATION>Hollywood</ORGANIZATION>.
   For 10 years she starred in a string of popular musicals: ``Sing
Baby Sing,'' ``Stowaway'' (with <PERSON>Shirley Temple</PERSON>) ``On the Avenue,''
``Alexander's Ragtime Band,'' ``<PERSON>Sally</PERSON>, <PERSON>Irene</PERSON> and <PERSON>Mary</PERSON>,'' ``Rose of
<LOCATION>Washington Square</LOCATION>,'' ``<PERSON>Lillian Russell</PERSON>,'' ``Weekend in <LOCATION>Havana</LOCATION>'' and
more.
   Faye seldom watches her old movies on television (``I was never
a fan of me''). But she saw one recently that she remembered
fondly, the wonderfully slapstick ``Hollywood Cavalcade'' (<DATE>1939</DATE>).
   ``I really enjoyed seeing that one again,'' she said. ``I had
forgotten how funny (<PERSON>Buster</PERSON>) <PERSON>Keaton</PERSON> was. He was a genius who never
got his due in Hollywood.''
   She has less pleasant memories of her relations with studio boss
<PERSON>Darryl Zanuck</PERSON>.
   ``I wanted to do something more mature, but <PERSON>Zanuck</PERSON> didn't see it
that way,'' she said. ``They were making lots of money with
pictures that <PERSON>Betty Grable</PERSON> and myself were doing, all those
musicals. Always it was the same story. We changed costumes and
leading men, and off we'd go and make another one.''
   ``The only chance I had (for a dramatic role) was `Fallen Angel'
(<DATE>1945</DATE>). That was a good, meaty part. But when I finally saw it on
the screen, I was on the cutting room floor.''
   Faye was a victim of the big-studio era, when stars were
pigeon-holed. Her musicals were a studio staple, so <PERSON>Zanuck</PERSON> refused
to change the formula until ``Fallen Angel,'' a box-office failure.
Because of <PERSON>Zanuck</PERSON>'s cuts, no one will ever know whether Faye could
have succeeded in drama.
   And Faye left. She never went back.
   She and her husband starred for a decade on their top-rated
radio program, ``The <PERSON>Alice Faye-Phil Harris</PERSON> Show.'' She was a
frequent guest on television and returned to Fox for the <DATE>1962</DATE>
musical version of ``State Fair,'' with a score by <PERSON>Rodgers</PERSON> and
<ORGANIZATION>Hammerstein</ORGANIZATION>. In more recent times, she toured in ``Good News,''
first with <PERSON>John Payne</PERSON> and then with <PERSON>Don Ameche</PERSON>.
   For many years <PERSON>Faye</PERSON> and her husband have lived in <LOCATION>Rancho Mirage</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Harris</PERSON>, 85, often travels to golf tournaments.
</TEXT>
