BALLET  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     What she's constructing looks like a tonneau cover for a small aircraft.
However, it's the armor of a large dragon.;    Powered by 13 children, this is
the Jabberwock, namesake of <PERSON>Lewis Carroll</PERSON>'s epic poem, "Jabberwocky" -- one of
the core numbers of "The Adventures of Alice," the <DATE>spring</DATE> production of <ORGANIZATION>San
Jose Dance Theater</ORGANIZATION>, which plays this weekend at the CPA.;    Traditionally,
SJDT performs a classical story ballet, such as "Sleeping Beauty," for its
<DATE>spring</DATE> season.;    But "Alice" is its most ambitious effort yet: an all-new
production whose costumes and sets were built from the ground up, with a
commissioned score by <ORGANIZATION>Santa Clara University</ORGANIZATION> composer <PERSON>Henry Mollicone</PERSON> and
original choreography by <PERSON>Jody White</PERSON>, a well-known dance teacher from Fairfax.;
   Most of its <MONEY>$125,000</MONEY> cost has gone into an elaborate production constructed
by an army of parents.;    Like all San Jose Dance Theater productions, this
is a showcase for young dancers, drawn from schools all over the <LOCATION>South Bay</LOCATION>.
The goal of the company is to give a professional-quality performing
experience to as many as possible. White says her task has been to create
"choreography that children could do that would not make them nervous.";   
That doesn't mean it's easy. In <ORGANIZATION>SJDT</ORGANIZATION>'s rehearsal space in a renovated
warehouse at Ninth and <PERSON>Taylor</PERSON> streets, 16 preteens rehearse the lobster
quadrille, an intricate figure dance inspired by the courtly minuet. "All
right, ladies, collect your claws," calls the wardrobe assistant.;    Next
door, 17 smaller children march through the drill-team maneuvers of the deck
of cards, learning from rehearsal assistant <PERSON>Kim Gardner</PERSON> how to make sure
they're in a straight line.;    How many children are there in "Alice"? "I
would say about 1,275," says White, whose sharp nose and close-cropped hair
make her look like one of the <ORGANIZATION>Keebler</ORGANIZATION> cookie elves.;    Actually, there are
120, multiplied about threefold by parents and siblings, and they've given all
their free time to it for months.;    Since the middle of <DATE>January</DATE>, White has
come down from <LOCATION>Fairfax</LOCATION> every <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, and the dancers worked with
her until <TIME>late evening</TIME>. She'd stay over to start the <DATE>Sunday</DATE> rehearsal at <TIME>10:30
a.m.</TIME> and drive back to <LOCATION>Fairfax</LOCATION> in the <TIME>afternoon</TIME>. During the week, her work was
reinforced by her two rehearsal assistants, <PERSON>Gardner</PERSON>, who has danced with
<ORGANIZATION>Margaret Wingrove Dance Company</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Oakland Ballet</ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON>Kristin Elliot.</PERSON>;    As
the kids rehearse, their parents and others man the oars of an immense galley,
sewing costumes, constructing masks and props, building sets.;    The music
was composed in long-distance telephone calls. White would call <PERSON>Mollicone</PERSON> and
tell him the plan for each scene, how much music she wanted and what kind.
He'd write, call her back and sing it to her. The kids rehearsed from a
work-tape on which <PERSON>Mollicone</PERSON> played the piano and sang the instrumental solos
and even sound effects such as the sobs of the Mock Turtle.;    The idea for
"Alice" came from SJDT's artistic director, <PERSON>Paul Curtis</PERSON>. " '<PERSON>Alice</PERSON>' lends
itself to imaginative effects," says White, who conflated "Alice's Adventures
in <LOCATION>Wonderland</LOCATION>" and "Through the Looking-Glass" for the ballet. She and
lighting designer <PERSON>Brad Belleville</PERSON>, for instance, devised a dazzling war for
the chess pieces, all done in strobe lights.;    In translating it into dance,
she tried to select episodes that could be expressed in movement. The ballet
includes such danceable passages as the lobster quadrille, the chess game and
"Jabberwocky," whose slithy toves gyre and gimble in the wabe. ("Don't be
classical," White chided the dancers at one rehearsal. "Do it like a tove
would do it.");    The costumes were designed by <PERSON>Shawn Stuart</PERSON>, <PERSON>Curtis</PERSON>'
longtime partner, who also thought up the idea for its ingenious, economical
sets. The scenery, designed and built by <PERSON>George Pettit</PERSON>, consists of seven
periaktoi -- three-sided, 10-foot-high movable pillars, whose name and concept
come from the Hellenistic theater of the first and second centuries <ORGANIZATION>A.D. Each</ORGANIZATION>
has a man inside, who walks it around the stage; there's a different
configuration for each stopping place in <LOCATION>Alice</LOCATION>'s journey.;    The ballet's
familiar characters include <LOCATION>Tweedledum</LOCATION> and Tweedledee, the Mock Turtle and the
<ORGANIZATION>Gryphon</ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION>White Rabbit</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Caterpillar</ORGANIZATION>, the Queen of Hearts and the
White Knight.;    <ORGANIZATION>Alice</ORGANIZATION> will be danced by <PERSON>Sharon Wehner</PERSON>, a 15-year-old
sophomore at <ORGANIZATION>Live Oak High School</ORGANIZATION>. A third-year company member, <PERSON>Wehner</PERSON> has
been a snowflake and a demi-soloist in the divertissement of the annual
"Nutcracker.";    <PERSON>Ralph White</PERSON>, the choreographer's husband, an actor
accustomed to working in dance, plays the White Knight. Her son, <PERSON>David
Roxander</PERSON>, who just retired after 18 years with the <ORGANIZATION>National Ballet of Canada</ORGANIZATION>,
is dancing the <PERSON>Beamish</PERSON> Boy, slayer of the fierce Jabberwock.;    "It's the
first time in many years we've worked together as a family," said White -- and
how appropriate for a ballet that's intended as a family affair.;  The
Adventures of <LOCATION>Alice</LOCATION>; <LOCATION>San Jose Dance Theater</LOCATION>; When: 8 tonight, <TIME>2 p.m.</TIME>
<DATE>Saturday-Sunday</DATE>; Where: Center for the Performing Arts, 255 <LOCATION>Almaden Blvd.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>San
Jose</LOCATION>; Tickets: <MONEY>$10</MONEY>-<MONEY>$25</MONEY>. (408) 293-5665  </TEXT>
