<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   Love Conquers Almost All
   ----
   By Merle Rubin
</HL>
<DATE>
12/11/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<LP>
   Apart from Gothic romances, there are not many novels
these days that celebrate the escapist theme of love as a
magic cure-all defying common sense. Far more novelists seem
to be concerned with demonstrating how romantic delusions can
deprive people -- especially women -- of freedom, peace of
mind, and, occasionally, life and limb. Yet, in her third
novel, "Temples of Delight," (Grove Weidenfeld, 311 pages,
$19.95), the South African-born Barbara Trapido, who's lived
in England since 1963 and deftly appropriated the polished
style of sophisticated British social comedy, applies her
sharp sense of social nuances and her dry wit to advance the
old-fashioned proposition that love conquers all.
   Alice Pilling is a bright, blond, levelheaded English
schoolgirl, whose adolescent world is transformed by the
arrival of a new girl in the middle of the term: Veronica
Bernadette McCrail, who styles herself "Jem" (after the
"jem-sengwiches" in P.G. Wodehouse, as she glibly informs her
incredulous teachers). In a school full of scrubbed,
upper-middle-class girls mainly interested in hockey matches,
Jem comes to class reading Lampedusa's "The Leopard" and
enchants Alice with astonishing stories of a French mother
who was "rudely forced" in the woods and a handsome father
who shaves to Gregorian chants and is so hyper-literary that
he thinks news reports on the decline of the pound refer to
the health of Ezra Pound.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Alice is charmed by everything about her precocious new
friend, from her "exotic" background to her enthusiastic
disquisitions on the wonders of <ORGANIZATION>Mozart</ORGANIZATION>'s "Magic Flute." Then,
one day, <PERSON>Jem</PERSON> disappears when the school authorities pass her
over and award what should have been her scholarship to a
prim, mean-spirited grade-grubber. A light goes out of
<ORGANIZATION>Alice</ORGANIZATION>'s life. Outwardly, she proceeds as normal, going on to
<LOCATION>Oxford</LOCATION>, acquiring a suitable fiance (two, in fact, seriatim,
as in a fairytale). Everything looks right, but nothing feels
right. Then, a bizarre set of circumstances brings Jem back
into <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s life, and through her, an exotic, high-strung
Italian-American man called <PERSON>Angeletti</PERSON>, who seems like <PERSON>Mr.
Wrong</PERSON>, but in the curious dream-logic of this boldly
anti-realist novel, turns out to be exactly the right person
to rekindle <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s lost capacity for joy and delight.
   Invoking ghostly parallels with "The Magic Flute"
(Angeletti as <ORGANIZATION>Sarastro</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Jem</PERSON> as a benign Queen of the <TIME>Night</TIME>),
<PERSON>Ms. Trapido</PERSON> invites us to suspend our customary suspicions of
overly charismatic people and our usual disbelief in
improbable happy endings. The aura of preciousness and
artifice surrounding the proceedings is occasionally a little
cloying, but <PERSON>Ms. Trapido</PERSON> has a light, sure touch that enables
her to carry it off with panache. By portraying the genuine
difficulties of Alice's various relationships -- the
deadening qualities of the seemingly sensible ones, the
liberating intensities of those that are based on romantic
love -- she manages to make the improbable surprisingly
possible.
   <PERSON>Asher</PERSON> and <PERSON>Sarah Rose</PERSON>, the happily married, middle-aged
<LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> Jewish couple in <PERSON>Susan Sussman</PERSON>'s second novel, "Time
Off from Good Behavior," (Pocket Books. 274 pages, <MONEY>$20</MONEY>), are
as humorously "real" as the middle-aged and middle class are
expected to be in novels of this kind. Asher is a lovable guy
who's just sold the family company he built up from scratch.
Having made <MONEY>$20 million</MONEY> from the sale, <PERSON>Asher</PERSON> is looking
forward to travel and romance with his wife. Their children
have grown up. They are still in love. They've earned the
right to enjoy themselves.
   There's a slight glitch: After years of working on the
fringes of the costume design industry, <PERSON>Sarah</PERSON> has landed a
job designing clothes for a feature-length film. This is her
big chance, and she expects her husband to be as supportive
of her career as she was of his. Asher, however, feels lost
without his company to fuss over.
   Anxious to succeed in her work, <PERSON>Sarah</PERSON> sends <PERSON>Asher</PERSON> off to
<LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> with her "permission" to have an affair if he likes:
time off for years of good behavior as a faithful husband and
devoted family man. Sarah herself finds temptation in the
form of a dashing set designer, who could take his pick from
hordes of ingenues but seems to prefer <PERSON>Sarah</PERSON>'s mature charms.
   Even with her husband out of the house, <PERSON>Sarah</PERSON> can scarcely
concentrate on her work because of the incessant nagging of
her ailing mother, a self-dramatizing 78-year-old former
actress. It soon becomes clear that the real problem isn't
<PERSON>Sarah</PERSON>'s hapless, self-effacing spouse, but her prima donna of
a mother.
   The story is narrated alternately by <PERSON>Sarah and Asher</PERSON>, who
unfortunately sound very much alike. <PERSON>Ms. Sussman</PERSON> relies on
heavy doses of wisecracking, supposedly self-deprecatory
humor that only thinly disguises her characters' basic,
unflappable self-satisfaction. Still, this novel has its
funny moments of desperation, and its moments of wisdom that
come from having survived the desperation. As <PERSON>Sarah</PERSON> tells her
own daughter, who is on the verge of a divorce, "You show me
a woman who hasn't fantasized getting in the car and leaving
home and I'll show you a woman who doesn't drive. . . . But
if you love someone, you get through it."
</TEXT>
