<DESCRIPT>  PAST; TELEVISION; CELEBRITY; DEATH; OBITUARY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  George Gobel, the sad-eyed comic with the flat-top haircut whose battles with
his TV wife, "Spooky Old Alice," added a dimension to 1950s domestic warfare,
died Sunday at 71.;    Sam Honigberg, his friend and publicist for nearly 40
years, said Gobel had suffered a series of strokes, which left him unable to
walk, and had undergone surgery nearly a month ago to determine whether his
mobility could be improved.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SINGING COMEDIAN GEORGE GOBEL DIES
DEADPAN HUMOR WAS TV HIT IN '50S  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "He may have had another stroke" and died at <ORGANIZATION>Encino Hospital</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Los
Angeles</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Honigberg</PERSON> said.;    <PERSON>Gobel</PERSON> had several nicknames during his long
career, which began when he was 11 and sang as "Little <PERSON>George Gobel</PERSON>" on
radio's "The <ORGANIZATION>National Barn Dance</ORGANIZATION>.";    He next became "Lonesome George,"
singer of sad cowboy ballads in which he would pick at his guitar while pining
for lost loves or evenings on the prairie.;    On television, 20-plus years
later, <PERSON>Gobel</PERSON> enriched the language with such phrases as "Well, I'll be a dirty
bird" and "You don't hardly get those no more." His underplayed, deadpan humor
contrasted with other TV comics of the day -- frenetic entertainers such as
<PERSON>Milton Berle</PERSON> and Red Skelton.;    His flair as a teller of tall tales, kept
him at, or near, the top of the ratings throughout the 1954-to-1960 run of
"The <PERSON>George Gobel</PERSON> Show.";    The <ORGANIZATION>NBC</ORGANIZATION> show, which won him an Emmy in <DATE>1955</DATE>,
started with an opening monologue, a sketch or song by a guest star and then
the inevitable aggravation he suffered at the hands of his wife, <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>. Had
<ORGANIZATION>CBS</ORGANIZATION>'s "Gunsmoke" not been his opposition, his series might have lasted even
longer.;    <PERSON>George Leslie Gobel</PERSON> was born in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> to a grocer father and a
mother who taught piano.;    <PERSON>Gobel</PERSON>'s interest in entertainment began as a
child, when he imitated his father's customers. He learned to play guitar in
grammar school and sang in a church choir. The choir appeared on a <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>
radio station, and his solo won him an invitation to the <ORGANIZATION>Barn Dance</ORGANIZATION> program.; 
  <PERSON>Gobel</PERSON> learned to fly and in <DATE>1943</DATE> enlisted in the <ORGANIZATION>Army Air Corps.</ORGANIZATION>;    In
<DATE>1961</DATE>, <PERSON>Gobel</PERSON> was featured on Broadway in a musical adaptation of <PERSON>George
Abbott</PERSON>'s "Three Men on a Horse," retitled "Let It Ride." He also toured in
"The Odd Couple" and "The Last of the Red Hot Lovers.";    His films included
"The Birds and the Bees" and "I Married a Woman." He did many voice-overs for
TV commercials and was a regular on the syndicated "Hollywood Squares" game
show.;    There was a real <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> in <PERSON>Gobel</PERSON>'s life -- high school sweetheart,
<PERSON>Alice Humecki</PERSON>, whom he married in <DATE>1942</DATE>. She and their two daughters, son and
three grandchildren survive him.  </TEXT>
