<CAPTION>  Photos (3); Photos by Eugene Louie -- Extra; Included on Campbell Historic
Home Tour will be the PHOTO: upstairs bathroom, top, and PHOTO: master
bedroom, far left, and PHOTO: kitchen nook of the Young-Sartorette House. (all
color)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CAMPBELL; HISTORY; HOUSING; SHOW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A walk through a portion of the past will be held this Saturday during the
Campbell Historic Home Tour.;    Six houses displaying architectural styles of
the 1800s and the 1920s and 1930s are included on the tour. All the homes are
on the Campbell Historic Register and several have been meticulously restored
to preserve details of those bygone times.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Extra 3  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOME TOUR STEPS INTO CAMPBELL'S PAST
SIX-SITE EVENT TO BENEFIT AINSLEY PROJECT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EX1/6, EX2/7  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The houses will be open for viewing between noon and <TIME>5 p.m</TIME>. The tour can
start at any of the homes.;    Tickets are <MONEY>$10</MONEY> on the day of the tour. A
hostess will greet visitors at each of the homes and provide historical
accounts of the house and interesting facts about the former occupants.;   
The event is sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION>Campbell Historic Museum Association</ORGANIZATION> and the
<ORGANIZATION>Campbell Historic Preservation Board</ORGANIZATION>, and proceeds will benefit the <ORGANIZATION>Ainsley
House Restoration</ORGANIZATION> and Museum Project.;    The English Tudor cottage revival
house, and a carriage house, were donated to the city of <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION> by the
granddaughters of <ORGANIZATION>J.C. Ainsley</ORGANIZATION>, the original owner and a pioneer in fruit
canning, drying, and packing. The <ORGANIZATION>Ainsley House</ORGANIZATION> was moved last <DATE>November</DATE> to its
new location in <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION>'s Civic Center, where it is being renovated for use
as the <ORGANIZATION>Campbell Historical Museum.</ORGANIZATION>;    A variety of funding sources are being
used to pay for the roughly <MONEY>$2 million</MONEY> renovation. The <ORGANIZATION>Campbell Historical
Museum Association</ORGANIZATION>, which will have offices in the <ORGANIZATION>Ainsley House</ORGANIZATION>, has agreed
to raise <MONEY>$1 million.</MONEY>;    <ORGANIZATION>The Campbell Historic Home Tour</ORGANIZATION> has been organized by
a <ORGANIZATION>Museum Association</ORGANIZATION> committee chaired by <PERSON>Joanna Herz.</PERSON>;    <PERSON>Herz</PERSON> and her
husband, <PERSON>Rudi</PERSON>, own the <ORGANIZATION>Young-Sartorette House</ORGANIZATION>, one of the homes on the tour.
The couple moved the English cottage-style house from its original location on
<LOCATION>South Bascom Avenue</LOCATION> <DATE>10 years ago</DATE> to its present location at <ORGANIZATION>1888 White Oaks
Road.</ORGANIZATION>;    "Some people might think of preservation with a '<ORGANIZATION>George Washington
Slept Here</ORGANIZATION>' mentality, but it is equally important to realize what working men
and women did for our country and what made <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> great," said Herz.;   
"This tour in <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION> features the former homes of working people; the
orchardists, farmers, cannery people who were the economic backbone of this
area. By preserving these homes, and others like it, we can show how these
people lived and what was important to them. And, in seeing some of the values
they had, we can incorporate them into our lives today.";    <ORGANIZATION>The
Young-Sartorette House</ORGANIZATION> was designed and built in <DATE>1928</DATE> for <ORGANIZATION>Earl</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Virginia
Young</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Earl Young</PERSON>, a farmer and insurance agent, was also active in the <LOCATION>Prune</LOCATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Apricot Growers Association</ORGANIZATION>. W.C. and <PERSON>Colette Sartorette</PERSON> purchased the
home in the <DATE>1930s</DATE>. W.C. <PERSON>Sartorette</PERSON> was a longtime trustee in the <ORGANIZATION>Cambrian
School District</ORGANIZATION> and a leader in the building of 10 schools. Sartorette School
is named for him.;    The other houses on the tour are:;    (check) <ORGANIZATION>First
Ainsley House</ORGANIZATION>: The Queen <PERSON>Anne</PERSON> cottage was the first house <ORGANIZATION>J.C. Ainsley</ORGANIZATION> owned
after he came to <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1887</DATE>. Originally located at the corner of
<ORGANIZATION>Winchester Boulevard</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Campbell Avenue</ORGANIZATION>, the house is now located at 84 <ORGANIZATION>N.
Third St.</ORGANIZATION> The property was purchased in <DATE>1921</DATE> by the <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION> elementary school
district and moved to the rear of the property to make way for a new school
building. The district sold the house in <DATE>1930</DATE> to the only bidder, <PERSON>Antone
Ferro</PERSON>, the school janitor. Ferro moved the home to its current location. <PERSON>Barry
Shilman</PERSON> and <PERSON>Susan Blake</PERSON> purchased the home in 1977.;    (check) Galindo-Leigh
House: Listed on the <ORGANIZATION>National Register</ORGANIZATION>, the home at 140 <PERSON>Peter Drive</PERSON> was
started in the <DATE>1830s</DATE> by <PERSON>Juan Galindo</PERSON>, a Spaniard who added to the structure
over the years to house his 11 children. <PERSON>John D. Gueraz</PERSON> was the next owner and
his additions to the home reflect a Swiss heritage and <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION> French
plantation background. A British aristocrat, <PERSON>Delicia Leigh</PERSON>, was the next owner
and she added Victorian embellishments. <PERSON>Leigh Avenue</PERSON> is named for her family.
The house's current owner is Hilles Podesta.;    (check) <ORGANIZATION>Righter House</ORGANIZATION>:
Located at 599 <LOCATION>El Patio</LOCATION>, the house was built in <DATE>1896</DATE> for <ORGANIZATION>F.M.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Belle
Righter</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Righter</PERSON> was an advocate of farm cooperatives who wrote a pamphlet
that greatly influenced raisin growers in the state. The couple's son, <LOCATION>C.E.</LOCATION>
"Swede" <PERSON>Righter</PERSON> became <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION>'s first Olympic gold medalist as a member of
the <DATE>1920</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Rugby</ORGANIZATION> team. A railroad buff, <PERSON>F.M. Righter</PERSON> had the house built
facing the railroad tracks. <PERSON>W. Graham</PERSON> and <PERSON>Jane Wood</PERSON> purchased the home in
<DATE>1985.</DATE>;    (check) <PERSON>Ralph Hyde</PERSON> House: The <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> Craftsman bungalow at 227
<ORGANIZATION>Alice Ave.</ORGANIZATION> was home to <PERSON>Ralph</PERSON> and <PERSON>Maud Hyde</PERSON>, son and daughter-in-law of <PERSON>George
Hyde</PERSON>, local packing company owner, and his wife, <PERSON>Alice Hill Hyde</PERSON>, after whom
<ORGANIZATION>Alice Street</ORGANIZATION> is named. The <PERSON>Ralph Hydes</PERSON>, and later their son, <LOCATION>Homer</LOCATION>, owned the
<ORGANIZATION>Campbell Water Co.</ORGANIZATION> for many years. Homer <PERSON>Hyde</PERSON> was a former mayor of <ORGANIZATION>Campbell</ORGANIZATION>.
Rick and <PERSON>Jackie Costanzo</PERSON> purchased the home in <DATE>1983.</DATE>;    (check) <LOCATION>Kennedy
House</LOCATION>: A Spanish colonial style home at 61 <PERSON>Catalpa Lane</PERSON>, the house was built
in <DATE>1930</DATE> for <ORGANIZATION>Erle</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Bessie Kennedy</PERSON>. Kennedy, a successful farmer and property
owner, and his wife were well-known for their community involvement. When they
subdivided their ranch in the <DATE>1940s</DATE>, they curved Catalpa Lane around their
home rather than pay <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> to move it. Councilwoman <PERSON>Jeanette Watson</PERSON> and her
husband, <PERSON>Courtland</PERSON>, purchased the home in <DATE>1960.</DATE>;    During the tour,
refreshments will be served at one of the homes and a boutique featuring items
by several local organizations and individuals will be held at another.;   
<ORGANIZATION>The Downtown Campbell Business Association</ORGANIZATION> also will be displaying items
appropriate to the period of the various houses. The <ORGANIZATION>San Jose Model A Club</ORGANIZATION>
will display a variety of restored <DATE>1930s</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Ford</ORGANIZATION> automobiles.  </TEXT>
