<HL> Tax Report:
A Special Summary and Forecast
Of Federal and State Tax
Developments
---
By Scott R. Schmedel</HL>
<DD> 05/20/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> TAXES
INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
CONGRESS (CNG) </IN>
<TEXT>
   AND BOB AND CAROL and Ted and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> thought they knew all the angles? 

   (We borrow the familiar names to relate a gift-tax scam involving brothers.) 
One may give <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> a year each to any number of people, free of gift tax. 
So, in <DATE>1982 through 1985</DATE>, <PERSON>Bob</PERSON> and <PERSON>Carol</PERSON> each gave <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> to each of their two children and <PERSON>Ted</PERSON> and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s three children; Ted and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> each gave <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> to each of the five children. 
Also in <DATE>1982</DATE>, Ted and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> each gave <MONEY>$15,000</MONEY> (<MONEY>$5,000</MONEY> over the limit) to each of <PERSON>Bob</PERSON> and <PERSON>Carol</PERSON>; in <DATE>1983</DATE> and <DATE>1984</DATE>, Ted and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON> each gave <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> to each of Bob and <PERSON>Carol</PERSON>. 

   In the next episode, the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> audited the foursome, who claimed that only the <MONEY>$5,000</MONEY> excesses of <DATE>1982</DATE> were subject to gift tax. 
But in private ruling 8717003, the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> takes the couples to task and tax: The reciprocal transfers between families were related and generally equal. 
They doubled what each child got. 
Ted's and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s gifts to <PERSON>Bob</PERSON> and <PERSON>Carol</PERSON> in effect repaid gifts to <PERSON>Ted</PERSON> and <PERSON>Alice</PERSON>'s third child. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> found that each parent should be treated as having given each of his or her own children <MONEY>$20,000</MONEY> a year -- twice the exempt sum. 

   IRS WARNINGS to abusive-shelter investors are upheld by appeals judges. 

   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> <PERSON>Judge Neese</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Nashville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn.</LOCATION>, found that <ORGANIZATION>Mid-South Music Corp.</ORGANIZATION> promoted illegal shelters. 
But in <DATE>1985</DATE>, he also ordered the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> to pay damages for illegally revealing company tax information to investors; <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> letters, sent before it took public action against <LOCATION>Mid-South</LOCATION>, warned investors that they risked audits and penalties if they claimed the shelter deductions. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> turned to the sixth-circuit appeals court. 
Now a three-judge panel has held that the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>'s pre-filing notices didn't violate the confidentiality of <ORGANIZATION>Mid-South</ORGANIZATION>'s returns and has reversed the damage award. 
<PERSON>Judge Norris</PERSON> said the notices identified Mid-South as a shelter promoter, not a taxpayer, and gave "no indication" that its returns were being audited or investigated. 

   ANON. WRITES another hit: The official tax-act handbook. 

   The "General Explanation of the Tax Reform Act of <DATE>1986</DATE>, Prepared by the Staff of the <ORGANIZATION>Joint Committee on Taxation</ORGANIZATION>," or "blue book," is a best seller for the <ORGANIZATION>Government Printing Office</ORGANIZATION>. 
Some 13,450 copies of the first printing of 14,870 have been sold at <MONEY>$31</MONEY>, mailing included. 
Experts peruse the 1,379 pages, especially notes on probable technical corrections, to see how far the anonymous authors have advanced understanding of what <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> really meant. 

   But <PERSON>Uncle Sam</PERSON> can be undersold: Prentice-Hall, using "non-archival paper," sells a two-pound, 1.7-ounce facsimile at <MONEY>$16</MONEY> prepaid, including mailing; the GPO book weighs two pounds, 10.5 ounces. 
<ORGANIZATION>Commerce Clearing House</ORGANIZATION> offers a one-pound, 13.4-ounce facsimile at <MONEY>$15</MONEY>, plus mailing. 
Both publishers report brisk sales above the tens of thousands of copies given to their regular subscribers. 
Two publishers resell the GPO book-Bureau of <ORGANIZATION>National Affairs</ORGANIZATION> for <MONEY>$51</MONEY>, Tax Notes magazine for <MONEY>$48</MONEY> plus mailing. 

   Just out is a separate, 235-page explanation of <DATE>1986</DATE> technical corrections to past acts; GPO price, <MONEY>$6.50</MONEY>. 

   AFTER THEIR DIVORCE, <PERSON>Louise</PERSON> stayed on with <PERSON>Billy</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Indianapolis</LOCATION> to look after their seven kids. 
He paid all her expenses; they later had another child. 
She wasn't just employed as a housekeeper, as the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> argued, the <ORGANIZATION>Tax Court</ORGANIZATION> decided. 
It let <PERSON>Billy</PERSON> claim his ex-wife as a dependent. 

   MOVING ON: <PERSON>Roger Olsen</PERSON>, resigning <DATE>June 4</DATE> as assistant attorney general for tax, will join the <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> office of Fried, <PERSON>Frank</PERSON>, <PERSON>Harris</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Shriver &amp; Jacobson Aug.</ORGANIZATION> 1. 
<PERSON>John Murray</PERSON> is retiring as deputy assistant attorney general for tax this week to join an unidentified law firm. 

   INFORMATION RETURNS, such as the Form 1099 reports on interest payments by banks, must be filed in high-volume cases on magnetic tape or other "machine-readable" forms. 
New <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> rules say failure to comply will subject a payer to penalties for failing to file the reports at all. 

   ROYALTIES may be costly for software corporations that chose "S" status. 

   Tax revision created incentives for a closely held regular corporation to become an S corporation, taxed like a partnership. 
But many computer-programming concerns that get passive income -- royalties -- from licensing software fell unawares into a trap, says <PERSON>Charles Medallis</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Arthur Andersen &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, CPAs. 
They are successful concerns that ploughed profits into expansion and so had large earnings and profits on their books when they converted to S status. 

   The companies have run afoul of two S-corporation rules, <PERSON>Medallis</PERSON> says: First, if an S concern holds earnings and profits from its regular-corporation days, and over <PERCENT>25%</PERCENT> of gross receipts is passive income (royalties), the excess passive income is taxable to the company (instead of only to its owners) at the highest corporate rate. 
Second, if that happens for three straight years, the company's S status is canceled. 

   Companies that would have trouble paying out profits to owners may seek to change the law, <PERSON>Medallis</PERSON> says. 

   BRIEFS: The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> created an award plaque for law-enforcement people who make significant contributions to its criminal investigations. . . . 
The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> issued instructions for the required reporting of real-estate transactions on Form 1099-B. . . . 
<ORGANIZATION>The House Ways and Means</ORGANIZATION> oversight panel plans hearings in the <DATE>week of June 22</DATE> on exempt entities' taxable business activities. 

